article.description: Janel McCarville had 21 points and 15 rebounds to lead Minnesota (No. 16 ESPN/USA Today, No. 14 AP) to a 76-55 win over Michigan.
article.headline: Gophers hand Wolverines fourth straight loss
article.story:
ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Michigan coach Cheryl Burnett wasn't surprised to see a well-rounded effort from Minnesota on Sunday.

"We knew they were going to go inside on us, but they're also one of the best shooting teams I've seen in my coaching career," Burnett said after the Gophers (No. 16 ESPN/USA Today, No. 14 AP) defeated the Wolverines 76-55.

Janel McCarville had 21 points and 15 rebounds for the Gophers, who outrebounded Michigan 33-23. Minnesota also hit 7-of-14 3-point attempts and shot a scorching 75 percent in the second half.

"Right now I really think we have some good balance," Minnesota coach Pam Borton said. "I'm pleased with how we're moving the ball."

Minnesota (18-4, 8-2) played most of the game without second-leading scorer and rebounder Jamie Broback. She suffered a left ankle sprain with 15:10 remaining in the first half and didn't return until after the break. She played a total of 13 minutes and finished with seven points -- 6.5 below her average.

Liz Podominick, McCarville's backup at center, came off the bench to score 14 points.

"Liz was critical," Borton said. "With Jamie out she gave us a lot of minutes and she did a great job defensively, even though she was playing out of position."

Leading by six at the break, the Gophers came out and hit six of their first seven shots in the second half, including a pair of 3-pointers by Kelly Roysland, to take a 52-36 lead with 12:18 to play.

Minnesota made 15-of-20 field-goal attempts and 11-of-13 free-throw attempts in a red-hot second-half performance.

"We've always emphasized that the first four or five minutes of the second half is important," Borton said. "We played good basketball, we got a lead and we really were able to capitalize."

Roysland finished with 12 points. She also hit a pair of foul shots late in the first half to give her 27 consecutive made free throws, breaking Jodi Olson's Minnesota school record of 26 set during the 1988-89 and 1989-90 seasons.

Roysland later extended the streak to 31 consecutive made. Kelly Helvey and Tabitha Pool had 16 points each for Michigan (5-17, 1-10).

The Wolverines are in the middle of a schedule streak in which they play six consecutive games against teams that are nationally ranked and/or went to the NCAA Tournament last year.

Burnett said she remains confident in her team, despite a fourth consecutive loss and a 13th defeat in the last 14 games.

"Once again I thought we played a good half of basketball," she said. "So, to me, it's all defense. We have to figure out a way to stop somebody and we have to figure out a way to play through those first few minutes of the (second) half."
